SIMPLE: tulipomania
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tulipomania
<hw>Tu`lip*o*ma"ni*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Tulip</ets> + <ets>mania</ets>.]</ety> <def>A violent passion
for the acquisition or cultivation of tulips; -- a word said by Beckman
to have been coined by Menage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In Holland, in the first half of the 17th century, the
cultivation of tulips became a mania. It began about the year 1634, and,
like a violent epidemic, seized upon all classes of the community,
leading to disasters and misery such as the records of commerce or of
bankruptcies can scarcely parallel. In 1636, tulip marts had been
established in Amsterdam, Rotterdam, Haarlem, Leyden, and various other
towns, where tulip bulbs were sold and resold in the same manner as
stocks are on the Stock Exchange of London.</note>
<rj><au>Baird.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tulipomaniac</ent>⟦br⟧
